      "role": "user",
      "content": "hi i am looking at buying my first house and im confused about the different loan types. can u explain the difference between a fixed rate mortgage and an adjustable rate mortgage (arm)? specifically how do the interest rates and monthly payments change over the first 5 years if the rates go up?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A fixed-rate mortgage (FRM) and an adjustable-rate mortgage (ARM) are the two main types of loans, but they are not just different labels; they are two different *types of contracts* with different rules.\n\nWhen you buy a house, you are essentially signing a deal with the bank. In an FRM, the bank promises you a specific interest rate for the entire life of the loan, usually 30 years. If the market rates go up, your rate stays the same. In an ARM, the bank promises you a specific rate for a short period (like 5 years), but then the rate becomes \"adjustable\" and can change based on market conditions.\n\nThink of it like buying a car. An FRM is like buying a car with a fixed price tag that never changes, no matter what the market does. An ARM is like buying a car with a \"test drive\" price tag for the first five years, but then the price tag changes based on how the market feels.\n\n**How the rates and payments change over the first 5 years:**\n\nIf you choose an ARM, the first 5 years are usually the \"teaser\" period. During this time, the interest rate",
      "source": "target",
